##Selling vegetables, throwing vegetables, closing shops, the capital city food and beverage under the influence of the epidemic

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

Our correspondent, Zhang Xiaodi, reports from Beijing

Wuhan epidemic is still continuing, home quarantine is an important means to prevent the spread of the epidemic, and with the economic impact of self-evident, the retail, catering industry bear the brunt. Reporters recently visited Beijing and learned that, because no one to eat, as well as the cancellation of New Year's Eve dinner orders, selling vegetables, throwing dishes, closed has become a helpless choice of the Beijing Restaurant Industry.

Since the fifth day of the Lunar New Year, Jin millions, a veteran beijing-based restaurant in Chaoyang District, has started selling vegetables outside its restaurant, a manager of the shop told the reporter rather helplessly: "originally wanted to rely on the new year to make some money, who knows what happened, this all lost. "

The reporter sees, the place that the guest queues up to wait for a seat in the past is now heaped with vegetable, fruit, half-finished meat to wait. A manager of the store told the reporter that more than 400,000 yuan of goods were stored in the store for more than 400 tables to prepare for the New Year's Eve dinner.

"At special times, we can't force people to come and return their deposits, " said the manager, adding that the vegetables and meat, which were prepared at high prices years ago, are sold at a loss and those that can not be sold are thrown away.

As of February 4, the store had been selling vegetables for a week. The manager said it would take about a week for the store's stock to be processed.

The reporter saw that some of the Parsley and garlic sprouts displayed at the entrance of the shop were somewhat wilted. In response, the manager kept coming to buy food residents explained: "The weather is cold, take out as a sample, a moment of wilting, plastic bags have packaging is good, take from plastic bags. "

"How much is this chicken? " A customer asked, pointing to the CLINGFILM wrapped chicken. A waiter in the shop said: "This is garlic chicken, we are prepared for New Year's Eve dinner, a few days ago sold for 40 yuan, you take 35 yuan. " The waiter told reporters, usually such a chicken into a dish sold for more than 100 yuan.

Fish is also sold in accordance with the bar, the reporter learned that the shop to a catty 40,70,80 yuan to buy Mandarin Fish, turbot fish, and so on, now only by 30 ~ 40 yuan a processing; 6 yuan a Catty to buy only 5 yuan a catty Papaya.

Reporters learned that the restaurant, which used to have a daily turnover of nearly 20,000 yuan, has only been able to earn about 2,000 yuan a day from the take-out Menus and the ingredients sold since the outbreak. "These simply can not cope with one day's invisible expenses. " The store manager told the reporter that the rent, the staff on duty wages plus water and electricity charges, one day down the expenses of about 10,000 yuan.

The manager of the restaurant for more than 10 years sighed: "It is estimated that we will not take a breath until July. Wasn't that the case with SARS? "

"We didn't expect the outbreak to reach Beijing, otherwise we wouldn't have had so much food, " the manager said repeatedly in an interview. "If we had known this would happen, we would have at least had this much to lose as soon as our employees were on vacation and the doors were closed. "

But life is not "knew" , just like a Xinyuecai restaurant near Panjiayuan Subdistrict's optician city, which also stocked up on ingredients years ago, this restaurant is a seafood restaurant. The head chef of the restaurant told reporters that over 10 days since the Chinese New Year, not a guest patronized them, booking more than 300 tables have been returned by the guests.

Despite the fact that the main seafood restaurant has been hit harder by the outbreak, which is suspected to have originated from the south China Seafood Market in Wuhan, the restaurant manager, the on-duty waiter and the chef are opening their doors every day, but "nobody cares" , the chef reluctantly shook his head. The store manager told the reporter that their daily loss is about 30,000 yuan. Seafood is not like vegetables that can be taken out to sell, for a long time, once can not eat, can only be thrown. "It's been a tough couple of years, " the manager said. "I just hope it's over soon. ".

The city's most iconic restaurant street, Florida -- also dominated by crayfish and other seafood -- is in recession. Only Huajiayi Garden and Xiaolongkan hot pot restaurant barely open, other restaurants such as "Hu da restaurant" featuring lobster, crab and other seafood features have chosen from the first day of the New Year "closed" . In the past, there was a long line of "Hu da" in front of the store, no longer the same situation as before. There was only one attendant in the store to answer the phone and play with the phone in a boring way.

And to "baked crayfish" as a feature of the "Fishing Niang" restaurant also chose to close shop.

"opening stores is more costly than closing them, " the manager of a noodle shop in Shuangjing Fuli Mall told reporters that she chose to stay on duty during the Spring Festival because she did not expect the epidemic would affect Beijing. She thought she could earn three salaries, as a result, the restaurant chose to close the shop for a holiday, even without a salary. The shopkeeper told the reporter that from the first day of the New Year to the tenth day of the New Year, it was sparse. There were no more than 50 guests in the shop. The Cook and the waiter were all waiting. In order to boil up the soup, wash the vegetables, cut them and prepare them, and the back-hall oven and other machines had to be turned on completely, water and electricity consumption, it is not worthwhile, the boss had to choose to close the shop, closed to the staff holiday, at least to save wages.

When the reporter interviews, this shopkeeper is arranging some just to fill the meal the lunch box. "these are for the staff who are left behind and are ready to be sent to them. It's a pity that they throw away everything they can eat in the kitchen fridge, but there's nothing they can do about it. "

Meituan takeout a non-local deliveryman also chose to stay in Beijing during the Chinese New Year. He told the reporter that compared to this time last year, his take-out order volume was greatly reduced, and the delivery fee was high during the Chinese New Year, this time last year he was making eight hundred a day; now he's only making a hundred a day. "I sacrificed the chance to be with my family. I didn't expect it, " he said.
